ings:** Spans the company\'s truth-seeking frontier large language model (*Grok*), AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, and *X* (the real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform).\n\n### 3. How Segments are Defined and Evaluated\nThe company\'s segments are defined by how the **Chief Operating Decision Maker (CODM)**—which is the company\'s **Chief Executive Officer**—organizes the business, manages resource allocations, and measures performance.\n\n*   **Primary GAAP Metric (Resource Allocation):** The CODM assesses performance and allocates resources based on **Segment Income (Loss) from Operations**. This is evaluated by comparing actual income/loss from operations against historical results and previously forecasted financial information. *(Note: The CODM does not evaluate the segments using asset or liability metrics).*\n*   **Key Non-GAAP Metric (Internal Planning & Investor Evaluation):** Management also heavily relies on **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** for internal planning, forecasting, and evaluating operating performance. It is defined as *Segment Income (Loss) from Operations* excluding the following items:\n    1. Depreciation and amortization\n    2. Share-based compensation\n    3. Restructuring charges\n    4. Impairments\n*   **Capital Expenditures Tracking:** The company also tracks and reports segment-level capital expenditures to monitor the heavy infrastructure investments required for each segment (e.g., launch pads and Starship facilities for Space; satellite deployments for Connectivity; and GPU/data center expansions for AI).',
