    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="Based on the provided financial document excerpts, here is the detailed discussion regarding the useful lives of assets, depreciation methods, satellite useful life, and asset impairment:\n\n### **Useful Lives of Assets and Depreciation Methods**\n*   **General Depreciation Method:** Property, plant, and equipment (PP&E) are stated at cost less accumulated depreciation. The Company primarily uses the **straight-line method** over the estimated useful lives of the assets. \n*   **Exceptions:** \n    *   **Flight vehicles and spacecraft** are depreciated based on the expected number of *average flights* for each vehicle rather than a time-based metric.\n    *   **Leasehold improvements** are depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n*   **Estimated Useful Lives Schedule:**\n    *   **Servers and networking equipment:** 5 - 6 years\n    *   **Satellites:** 3 - 5 years\n    *   **Machinery and equipment:** 3 - 10 years\n    *   **Flight vehicle hardware:** 5 - 25 flights\n    *   **Data center infrastructure:** 20 - 25 years\n    *   **Launch sites:** 7 - 20 years\n    *   **Buildings and improvements:** 30 years\n    *   **Leasehold improvements:** Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease\n*   **Revisions and Capitalization:** Management periodically reviews useful life estimates with engineering and operations teams. If useful lives or expected flights are revised, depreciation rates are adjusted accordingly. Routine maintenance is expensed as incurred, but significant refurbishments and enhancements that extend an asset's life or functionality are capitalized and depreciated ratably. Capitalized interest associated with significant construction projects is also depreciated over the asset's useful life.\n\n### **Satellite Useful Life**\n*   **Lifespan Characteristics:** The useful life of satellites is inherently shorter than the information technology systems and infrastructure they host. Consequently, the Company must periodically launch replacement satellites, which may truncate the effective lifespan of the underlying hosted IT infrastructure.\n*   **Estimation Factors:** Satellite useful lives are estimated using engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, design enhancements across generations, constellation density evolution, and planned transitions to newer technology.\n*   **Specific Estimates:** The Company estimates a **5-year useful life** for broadband satellites and a **3-year useful life** for first-generation mobile satellites.\n*   **Sensitivity Analysis:** A one-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would have impacted operating income by approximately **$480 million** for the year ended December 31, 2025, and **$170 million** for the three months ended March 31, 2026.\n\n### **Asset Impairment**\n*   **Evaluation Methodology:** The Company evaluates PP&E for impairment whenever events or circumstances indicate that an asset's carrying value may not be recoverable. Indicators include significant planned changes in asset use, technological developments reducing asset utility, declines in forecasted cash flows, and negative industry or economic trends.\n*   **Recognition of Charges:** Impairment is assessed at the lowest level with largely independent cash flows. If estimated future cash flows fall below the carrying value, an impairment charge is recognized for the amount the carrying value exceeds the estimated fair value. Routine disposals, scrapping, and gateway decommissions are charged to Cost of Revenue or SG&A, while impairments outside the normal course of business are charged to Impairment expenses.\n*   **Specific Impairment Events & Financial Impacts:**\n    *   **Space & Connectivity Segments (2025 & 2024):** The Company recorded impairment charges of **$38 million** (2025) and **$63 million** (2024) related to the write-off of a damaged flight vehicle (Space segment) and an abandoned production line and damaged satellite hardware (Connectivity segment). The 2025 decrease was also tied to the discontinuation of a Starlink Kit production line.\n    *   **AI Segment Restructuring (2024 & 2023):** The Company recorded **$36 million** (2024) and **$54 million** (2023) in Restructuring charges for leasehold improvements and office equipment due to facilities consolidation efforts.\n    *   **Space Segment (Q1 2025):** Recorded **$24 million** related to the write-off of damaged flight vehicles.\n    *   **Q1 2026:** No impairment charges related to PP&E were recorded.\n    *   *Note:* Overall, impairments on fixed assets were not considered material for the years ended December 31, 2025, 2024, and 2023, or for the three months ended March 31, 2026.",
