        output='Based on the provided financial statements and notes, here are the details regarding share-based compensation (SBC), expense recognition policies, and its treatment as an ongoing operational cost:\n\n### 1. Share-Based Compensation Details\n**Valuation Methodologies**\n*   **RSUs, RSAs, and ESPP:** Valued based on the fair market value of the Company’s common stock on the grant date.\n*   **Stock Options:** Valued using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model (inputs include stock price, risk-free interest rate, expected term, and volatility).\n*   **CEO Awards (Market/Performance/Service conditions):** Valued using a Monte Carlo simulation. Because the SpaceX and AI CEO Awards lack a defined performance period other than continued employment, an expected term midpoint of 30 years (from a 10–50 year range) was used.\n\n**Specific Award Programs & Modifications**\n*   **xAI Merger Conversions:** Outstanding xAI options, RSUs, and RSAs were converted into SpaceX equity awards at a **0.1433** ratio (on a pre-2026 Stock Split basis).\n*   **xAI Award (Elon Musk, Nov 2025):** A 12-tranche performance award tied to valuation milestones ($213B to $1,313B), a $2B capital raise condition, and a 10-year service period. The grant date fair value was **$2,205 million**, with $28 million expensed in 2025 before the award was terminated in March 2026.\n*   **X Employee RSUs (March 2023):** Originally tied to liquidity events (change in control or IPO). In 2025, the performance conditions were removed, triggering additional SBC expense.\n*   **CFO Award (Bret Johnsen, Jan 2026 Amendment):** 4 million performance-based options amended to vest based on achieving $10 billion increments in Adjusted EBITDA (from 2025–2029), followed by a 1-year service requirement.\n*   **SpaceX & AI CEO Awards:** As of March 31, 2026, performance milestones were deemed improbable, and no expense has been recognized.\n*   **Excluded Awards:** 14.5 million (2025), 38.3 million (2024), and 21.2 million (2023) awards were excluded from outstanding tables because their performance/market conditions had not been met.\n\n**Financial Impact & Capitalization**\n*   **Total SBC Expense:** $1,947M (2025), $784M (2024), and $679M (2023). For Q1 2026, it was $639M compared to $232M in Q1 2025.\n*   **By Line Item (2025):** R&D ($859M), SG&A ($835M), and Cost of Revenue ($253M).\n*   **By Segment (Q1 2026):** AI ($378M), Space ($145M), and Connectivity ($116M).\n*   **Capitalized SBC:** $154M (2025), $132M (2024), and $108M (2023) were capitalized to the balance sheet. Q1 2026 capitalized SBC was $60M.\n*   **Tax Impact:** No income tax benefit was recognized for SBC expenses due to a valuation allowance on U.S. deferred tax assets.\n\n### 2. SBC Expense Recognition Policies\n*   **Service Conditions Only:** Expense is recognized on a **straight-line basis** over the requisite service period.\n*   **Performance Conditions:** Expense is recognized on a **graded vesting basis** over the requisite service period, but *only* when the vesting of the award becomes probable.\n*   **Market Conditions (e.g., CEO Awards):** Expense is not recognized until the performance condition is deemed probable. Once met, it is recorded based on the requisite service period associated with the probable milestone.\n*   **Forfeitures:** The Company accounts for forfeitures **as they occur** rather than estimating them upfront.\n\n### 3. Discussion of SBC as a Recurring Cost\nWhile the text does not explicitly use the phrase "recurring cost," SBC is structurally embedded and treated as a fundamental, ongoing component of the Company\'s operating expenses:\n*   **Core Operational Integration:** SBC is consistently grouped with salaries and benefits as a standard element of "employee compensation costs." It is a permanent fixture in the cost structure of Cost of Revenue, R&D, and SG&A across all segments (Space, Connectivity, and AI).\n*   **Forward-Looking MD&A Projections:** Management projects that Connectivity\'s Cost of Revenue, R&D, and SG&A (all of which include SBC) will **increase in absolute dollars** as the business and revenue grow. However, they expect these costs to decrease as a *percentage of revenue* over time due to scaling efficiencies. This confirms SBC\'s role as an ongoing, scaling operational cost.\n*   **Non-Cash Add-Back for Performance Metrics:** SBC is consistently added back to GAAP Income from Operations to calculate **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** and Consolidated Adjusted EBITDA. Furthermore, the CFO\'s performance-based vesting metrics explicitly exclude SBC from the definition of Adjusted EBITDA. This highlights that management views SBC as a standard, recurring non-cash expense that must be adjusted for when evaluating core operational cash flow and performance.',
