        args='{"final_result": "## Two Situations Where Segment Adjusted EBITDA Comparisons Could Materially Misrepresent Economic Profitability\\n\\nThe SpaceX S-1 defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as segment income (loss) from operations excluding: (i) depreciation and amortization, (ii) share-based compensation, (iii) restructuring charges, and (iv) impairment. While useful as an operating-performance screen, this metric can materially distort cross-segment economic-profitability comparisons in at least two situations clearly evidenced by the filing\'s own data.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Situation 1: Divergent Capital Intensity — The Depreciation Add-Back Masks Vastly Different Cash-Capital Consumption Across Segments\\n\\nAdjusted EBITDA adds back depreciation and amortization, implicitly treating D&A as a non-cash charge that does not reflect ongoing economic cost. This assumption breaks down when a segment\'s **capital expenditures substantially exceed its depreciation**, meaning the segment is consuming cash capital far faster than the accounting add-back suggests.\\n\\nThe filing\'s own segment data for FY 2025 reveals dramatic disparities:\\n\\n| Segment | FY 2025 Capex | FY 2025 D&A | Capex / D&A Ratio | Adj. EBITDA | EBITDA − Capex |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| **Space** | $3,832M | $757M | **5.06×** | $653M | **$(3,179)M** |\\n| **Connectivity** | $4,178M | $2,376M | **1.76×** | $7,168M | **$2,990M** |\\n| **AI** | $12,727M | $3,568M | **3.57×** | $(1,237)M | **$(13,964)M** |\\n\\n**Why this misrepresents economic profitability:**\\n\\n- **Connectivity** appears to be the most profitable segment on an Adjusted EBITDA basis ($7,168M), and it *also* generates positive free cash flow after capex ($2,990M). Its capex-to-D&A ratio of 1.76× indicates a segment approaching a steady-state capital-replacement cycle, where depreciation is a reasonable proxy for maintenance capex.\\n\\n- **AI** reports Adjusted EBITDA of $(1,237)M — already negative — but this figure *still* dramatically understates the segment\'s cash-capital burn. Actual capex was $12,727M, meaning the segment consumed **$13,964M** in cash after EBITDA. The D&A add-back of $3,568M captures only 28% of the capital actually deployed.\\n\\n- **Space** reports *positive* Adjusted EBITDA of $653M, which could misleadingly suggest the segment is economically self-sustaining. In reality, capex of $3,832M (5.06× depreciation) means the segment consumed **$(3,179)M** in cash after EBITDA. The D&A add-back of $757M captures only 20% of actual capital outlays.\\n\\n**Comparing Space\'s positive $653M Adjusted EBITDA to Connectivity\'s $7,168M on a \\"profitability\\" basis is misleading**: Space is not generating cash above its capital needs — it is consuming $3.2 billion more in capital than its EBITDA suggests. An investor comparing segments on Adjusted EBITDA alone would not see that Connectivity is the *only* segment generating positive cash flow after capital expenditures.\\n\\nThis distortion is structurally inherent to EBITDA in any capital-intensive, growth-phase business where the asset base is expanding rapidly and depreciation (based on historical cost and useful-life estimates) systematically lags current capital deployment.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Situation 2: Disproportionate Share-Based Compensation Across Segments — The SBC Add-Back Obscures Real Economic Dilution Costs\\n\\nAdjusted EBITDA adds back share-based compensation (SBC), treating it as a non-cash expense irrelevant to operating performance. However, SBC represents **real economic cost to shareholders through equity dilution** and is a core component of talent retention — particularly in the AI segment. The filing\'s data shows SBC is distributed highly unevenly across segments:\\n\\n| Segment | FY 2025 SBC | FY 2025 Revenue | SBC as % of Revenue | Q1 2026 SBC | Q1 2026 Revenue | SBC as % of Revenue |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| **Space** | $515M | $4,086M | **12.6%** | $145M | $619M | **23.4%** |\\n| **Connectivity** | $369M | $11,387M | **3.2%** | $116M | $3,257M | **3.6%** |\\n| **AI** | $1,063M | $3,201M | **33.2%** | $378M | $818M | **46.2%** |\\n\\n**Why this misrepresents economic profitability:**\\n\\n- **The AI segment\'s SBC is 33–46% of its revenue**, meaning roughly one-third to nearly one-half of every dollar earned is used to compensate employees through equity. In Q1 2026, the AI segment reported an operating loss of $(2,469)M; the SBC add-back of $378M reduced that loss by 15% to arrive at Adjusted EBITDA of $(609)M. The segment is effectively funding its workforce with shareholder equity — a real economic transfer that EBITDA ignores entirely.\\n\\n- **Connectivity\'s SBC is only 3.2–3.6% of revenue**, meaning its Adjusted EBITDA of $7,168M (FY 2025) is far closer to its true economic earnings. The SBC add-back of $369M represents only **5.1%** of its Adjusted EBITDA.\\n\\n- **Space\'s SBC of $515M represents 78.9% of its Adjusted EBITDA of $653M** (FY 2025). Without the SBC add-back, Space reported a GAAP operating *loss* of $(657)M. Adjusted EBITDA converts this loss into an apparent profit — entirely through the exclusion of a recurring, structurally embedded compensation cost.\\n\\n**Comparing Space\'s $653M Adjusted EBITDA to Connectivity\'s $7,168M is misleading** because Space\'s \\"profitability\\" is an artifact of excluding $515M in equity compensation — without which the segment is operating at a loss. Meanwhile, Connectivity\'s profitability is robust to the SBC add-back because its SBC burden is minimal relative to its revenue base. An investor using Adjusted EBITDA to rank segment profitability would systematically overstate the economic performance of the AI and Space segments relative to Connectivity, because the dilution cost borne by shareholders to retain talent in those segments is invisible in the metric.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\n| Distortion | Root Cause | Most Affected Comparison |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **Capex ≫ Depreciation** | D&A add-back understates true capital consumption in growth-phase segments | Space and AI appear closer to Connectivity in profitability than cash-flow reality supports |\\n| **Disproportionate SBC** | SBC add-back ignores real dilution cost that varies 10×+ across segments | Space\'s EBITDA \\"profit\\" is entirely an artifact of excluding SBC equal to 79% of that EBITDA; AI\'s losses are understated by SBC equal to 33–46% of revenue |\\n\\nBoth situations are explicitly supported by the filing\'s own segment-level disclosures and are not speculative — they are arithmetic consequences of the Adjusted EBITDA definition applied to segments with fundamentally different capital and compensation structures.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Sources:**\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Two Situations Where Segment Adjusted EBITDA Comparisons Could Materially Misrepresent Economic Profitability\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as segment income (loss) from operations excluding: (i) depreciation and amortization, (ii) share-based compensation, (iii) restructuring charges, and (iv) impairment. While useful as an operating-performance screen, this metric can materially distort cross-segment economic-profitability comparisons in at least two situations clearly evidenced by the filing\'s own data.\n\n---\n\n### Situation 1: Divergent Capital Intensity — The Depreciation Add-Back Masks Vastly Different Cash-Capital Consumption Across Segments\n\nAdjusted EBITDA adds back depreciation and amortization, implicitly treating D&A as a non-cash charge that does not reflect ongoing economic cost. This assumption breaks down when a segment\'s **capital expenditures substantially exceed its depreciation**, meaning the segment is consuming cash capital far faster than the accounting add-back suggests.\n\nThe filing\'s own segment data for FY 2025 reveals dramatic disparities:\n\n| Segment | FY 2025 Capex | FY 2025 D&A | Capex / D&A Ratio | Adj. EBITDA | EBITDA − Capex |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Space** | $3,832M | $757M | **5.06×** | $653M | **$(3,179)M** |\n| **Connectivity** | $4,178M | $2,376M | **1.76×** | $7,168M | **$2,990M** |\n| **AI** | $12,727M | $3,568M | **3.57×** | $(1,237)M | **$(13,964)M** |\n\n**Why this misrepresents economic profitability:**\n\n- **Connectivity** appears to be the most profitable segment on an Adjusted EBITDA basis ($7,168M), and it *also* generates positive free cash flow after capex ($2,990M). Its capex-to-D&A ratio of 1.76× indicates a segment approaching a steady-state capital-replacement cycle, where depreciation is a reasonable proxy for maintenance capex.\n\n- **AI** reports Adjusted EBITDA of $(1,237)M — already negative — but this figure *still* dramatically understates the segment\'s cash-capital burn. Actual capex was $12,727M, meaning the segment consumed **$13,964M** in cash after EBITDA. The D&A add-back of $3,568M captures only 28% of the capital actually deployed.\n\n- **Space** reports *positive* Adjusted EBITDA of $653M, which could misleadingly suggest the segment is economically self-sustaining. In reality, capex of $3,832M (5.06× depreciation) means the segment consumed **$(3,179)M** in cash after EBITDA. The D&A add-back of $757M captures only 20% of actual capital outlays.\n\n**Comparing Space\'s positive $653M Adjusted EBITDA to Connectivity\'s $7,168M on a "profitability" basis is misleading**: Space is not generating cash above its capital needs — it is consuming $3.2 billion more in capital than its EBITDA suggests. An investor comparing segments on Adjusted EBITDA alone would not see that Connectivity is the *only* segment generating positive cash flow after capital expenditures.\n\nThis distortion is structurally inherent to EBITDA in any capital-intensive, growth-phase business where the asset base is expanding rapidly and depreciation (based on historical cost and useful-life estimates) systematically lags current capital deployment.\n\n---\n\n### Situation 2: Disproportionate Share-Based Compensation Across Segments — The SBC Add-Back Obscures Real Economic Dilution Costs\n\nAdjusted EBITDA adds back share-based compensation (SBC), treating it as a non-cash expense irrelevant to operating performance. However, SBC represents **real economic cost to shareholders through equity dilution** and is a core component of talent retention — particularly in the AI segment. The filing\'s data shows SBC is distributed highly unevenly across segments:\n\n| Segment | FY 2025 SBC | FY 2025 Revenue | SBC as % of Revenue | Q1 2026 SBC | Q1 2026 Revenue | SBC as % of Revenue |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Space** | $515M | $4,086M | **12.6%** | $145M | $619M | **23.4%** |\n| **Connectivity** | $369M | $11,387M | **3.2%** | $116M | $3,257M | **3.6%** |\n| **AI** | $1,063M | $3,201M | **33.2%** | $378M | $818M | **46.2%** |\n\n**Why this misrepresents economic profitability:**\n\n- **The AI segment\'s SBC is 33–46% of its revenue**, meaning roughly one-third to nearly one-half of every dollar earned is used to compensate employees through equity. In Q1 2026, the AI segment reported an operating loss of $(2,469)M; the SBC add-back of $378M reduced that loss by 15% to arrive at Adjusted EBITDA of $(609)M. The segment is effectively funding its workforce with shareholder equity — a real economic transfer that EBITDA ignores entirely.\n\n- **Connectivity\'s SBC is only 3.2–3.6% of revenue**, meaning its Adjusted EBITDA of $7,168M (FY 2025) is far closer to its true economic earnings. The SBC add-back of $369M represents only **5.1%** of its Adjusted EBITDA.\n\n- **Space\'s SBC of $515M represents 78.9% of its Adjusted EBITDA of $653M** (FY 2025). Without the SBC add-back, Space reported a GAAP operating *loss* of $(657)M. Adjusted EBITDA converts this loss into an apparent profit — entirely through the exclusion of a recurring, structurally embedded compensation cost.\n\n**Comparing Space\'s $653M Adjusted EBITDA to Connectivity\'s $7,168M is misleading** because Space\'s "profitability" is an artifact of excluding $515M in equity compensation — without which the segment is operating at a loss. Meanwhile, Connectivity\'s profitability is robust to the SBC add-back because its SBC burden is minimal relative to its revenue base. An investor using Adjusted EBITDA to rank segment profitability would systematically overstate the economic performance of the AI and Space segments relative to Connectivity, because the dilution cost borne by shareholders to retain talent in those segments is invisible in the metric.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Distortion | Root Cause | Most Affected Comparison |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Capex ≫ Depreciation** | D&A add-back understates true capital consumption in growth-phase segments | Space and AI appear closer to Connectivity in profitability than cash-flow reality supports |\n| **Disproportionate SBC** | SBC add-back ignores real dilution cost that varies 10×+ across segments | Space\'s EBITDA "profit" is entirely an artifact of excluding SBC equal to 79% of that EBITDA; AI\'s losses are understated by SBC equal to 33–46% of revenue |\n\nBoth situations are explicitly supported by the filing\'s own segment-level disclosures and are not speculative — they are arithmetic consequences of the Adjusted EBITDA definition applied to segments with fundamentally different capital and compensation structures.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
